Ismara's Doom — Writing Style Guide
The Core Principle: Thinking Out Loud
The single most important distinction in this campaign's writing is the difference between a character who has already thought something through and a character who is thinking right now, in front of you.
⚠ Notice: That opening sentence is a perfect example of arrived-at prose. It knows exactly where it's going before it starts. It is structured, complete, and would sound absurd spoken aloud. Nobody begins a sentence with "The single most important distinction in this campaign's writing is—" This is fine for a document meant to be read. It would be a character flaw if Wulfgar said it.
Real people don't know what they're going to say before they say it. The thought and the words arrive together — which means sometimes the words get ahead of the thought, sometimes the other way, sometimes a sentence starts in one direction and ends somewhere else because that's where the thinking went.
⚠ Notice: Even trimmed, this is still three parallel clauses in rhetorical order. A person actually fumbling through this idea would say something like "it's like — the words come out before you know what you're saying. Or the other way." And then stop. Because the other person understood. The document keeps going because it can't see your face.
When a character sounds rehearsed, they sound fake. Worse, they sound manipulative. The room hears it before anyone can name it.
⚠ Notice: "Worse, they sound manipulative" is a rhetorician's pivot to the more serious charge. It works on the page. Spoken, it sounds like someone performing cleverness. If Brunwulf said it you would not trust Brunwulf.
This can be used deliberately. A character who speaks in finished, precise, pre-arrived thoughts reads as controlled, calculating, or performing. Use this for Ismara. Use it for Calixto in his collector persona — warm, curious, too smooth. The style is the characterization.
Everyone else is figuring it out as they go.

Dialogue: What It Is and Isn't
What it isn't
Dialogue is not prose delivered through a character's mouth. It is not a vehicle for information. It is not a monologue that happens to have quotation marks around it.
⚠ Notice: Three sentences each beginning "It is not." Deliberate rhetorical device. Works here. If someone said this to you at a table they would sound like they were reciting something. Which they would be.
The most common failure mode produces sentences that are technically correct, emotionally complete, and completely unbelievable. Nobody says "I can hear it thinking, a little, when I do it. Not words. Just... presence." That sentence knows exactly what it means. Real people hitting the edge of what they can articulate don't find the exact right words. They find the almost-right ones, realize that's not it, and stop.
What it is
Dialogue is a character's thought process made audible — hesitations, corrections, sentences that don't finish, sentences that start over.
Wrong:
"The scarring follows the inflammation in a pattern I've never encountered. Almost looks like notation — structural, geometric. I've never seen tissue inflame this way."
Quintus knows exactly what he's saying. He's delivering a clue.
Right:
"The scarring follows the inflammation wrong. Rotjoint spreads outward from the joint — this is the reverse, almost like —" He sets down the instrument. "I don't have a word for that."
⚠ Notice: "Her hands" became just "the instrument." The room knows whose hands they are. The sentence doesn't need to say.
Quintus is doing his job and hitting something that doesn't fit. The clue is still there. The character is now real.

The Texture of Unfinished Thought
These are the tools. Use them sparingly — overuse produces a different kind of fake.
⚠ Notice: The format of this section — labeled techniques with definitions — is closer to Ismara than to Suvaris. Unavoidable in a reference document. Just know that the structure here demonstrates the register you're trying to avoid in everyone except Ismara and Calixto.

The trailing off
A character hits the edge of what they can articulate and stops.
"It's cold. The taste is — it's cold, but not like food is cold, it's —"
[Stop. Don't fill the silence. Let it land.]
⚠ Notice: Original had "She stops. Looks at her hands." Redundant. The silence after the dash is already the stop. "Her hands" tells us nothing the room doesn't already show. If you want the physical beat, it's: [Look down.] That's it.

The correction
A character says something, realizes it's not right, tries again — without acknowledging they changed anything.
"He was there every week. Every few days. Often."
[Don't rush past "often" — it's where they landed. Let it sit.]
⚠ Notice: Original ended with "More than you'd expect." Unnecessary. "Often" already implied frequency beyond normal. The extra sentence was explaining the joke.

The question that isn't
A character checks their own thought as they're forming it. They're not asking you. They're asking themselves out loud.
"Three weeks? Maybe three weeks."
[Look slightly past the person you're talking to — you're checking the memory, not them.]
⚠ Notice: Original ended "Does that sound right to you?" Cut entirely. There's one other person in the scene. Of course it's directed at them. The room handles that. The sentence ends at "three weeks" because that's where the thought ends.

The abandoned sentence
A character starts something and decides not to finish. Don't explain why. Don't soften it. Just stop.
"After the second one I thought about going to the guard, but —"
[Stop. Move on to something else or go quiet. Do not explain the "but."]

The wrong word
A character reaches for something, gets close but not exact, and doesn't notice.
"It's like it's still awake in there. Not awake. Present."
[Say "present" like you found it, not like you're correcting yourself. You think you got there.]
⚠ Notice: Original ended "It's present." — repeating the word for emphasis. Cut. The character thinks they've landed it. They move on. Repetition signals awareness of the correction. The point is they don't have that awareness.

The Room Does Work
This is the principle under all of the above.
A scene in a room has three things carrying it simultaneously: the words, the body, and the space between people. Written dialogue puts everything into the words because that's all it has. Spoken dialogue at a table has all three — which means the words can stop much earlier than a writer's instinct says they should.
What the room carries so the words don't have to:
Who is being spoken to
Whether something is a question or not
Whose hands, whose face, whose eyes
The emotional register of a pause
Whether a sentence is finished or deliberately cut off
What performance carries so the words don't have to:
Hesitation — [slow down before the hard part, don't announce it]
Shame — [don't make eye contact, find something else to look at]
Reaching for a word — [look up slightly, like the word is somewhere above you]
Landed on the wrong word — [say it with the same confidence as the right word would have]
Deciding not to finish — [just stop, don't trail off, stop]
The shorter the line, the more the performance has to carry. Trust yourself to carry it.

Register and Subtext
Subtext is what a character means versus what they say. It lives in the mismatch — between what someone says and how they say it, or between what they say and what the situation demands.
⚠ Notice: "Subtext is what a character means versus what they say." A complete definition delivered from outside the story. Useful here. If Calixto said it the players would know he was the villain immediately — and not in the interesting way.
Suvaris is ashamed. She doesn't say so. She hides the cloth when the Orc approaches. She explains before anyone asks. She says "I know it's wrong" — which is what people say when they're convincing themselves, not you.
Calixto is performing warmth. His warmth arrives a beat too fast. His questions are one degree more specific than curiosity requires. None of this is stated. It's in the rhythm.
⚠ Notice: "one degree more specific than curiosity requires" — precise formulation of something that should feel imprecise when you experience it. The guide gives you the analytical language so you can produce the un-analytical effect. If Jorleif said this sentence he would sound like he was reading a document about himself.
The rule: If the subtext can be read off the dialogue, there is no subtext. It lives in the gap.
⚠ Notice: "It lives in the gap." Aphorism. Ismara register. Works here, works in her notebook. Does not work in the mouth of anyone thinking in real time.

Ismara: The Exception
She writes. She has considered every word before she commits it. Her notes are short not because she has little to say but because she has already removed everything that isn't load-bearing.
This reads as slightly inhuman. Not cold — precise.
⚠ Notice: "Not cold — precise." That is an Ismara sentence. It corrects without apologizing. It arrives at the word and stops. Said in normal conversation it would sound performed. Which is exactly what Ismara sounds like. When your prose starts feeling like this paragraph, you're writing Ismara. When it feels like the Suvaris example, you're writing everyone else.
Her notes never trail off. Never correct themselves. When she asks the Khajiit something it is because she wants to observe the answer, not because she needs it.
The tell: Everyone else is figuring out what they think. Ismara already knows.

GM Prose: Notes vs. Writing
The same failure mode applies to GM-facing prose when it tells the GM how to feel instead of giving them material.
Wrong:
"Let this sit. They solved a real problem. The thing they were hired to stop is still happening."
A director talking to a camera. It explains the irony instead of trusting the GM to feel it.
Right:
"The Fever continues. Helgrid confirmed it — three new cases, same marks, same geometry. Calixto is dead and his workshop is ash and whatever is leaving these marks on people was never in those catacombs."
⚠ Notice: "Give the GM the facts. Trust them to run the silence." Still directing — but it's telling the GM what to do, not what to feel. Production notes can be arrived-at. Emotional stage directions cannot, because they're telling the GM how to perform something that should emerge from the material.
The rule: Say what happens. Say what is true. Don't say what it means. The GM is a writer too.

Read-Alouds
The one place where the prose is more literary — the GM is performing it, the room is listening, there's space for language to land. But the same logic applies: every sentence plants something or earns its place. If it sounds good and does nothing else, cut it.
End before the players' agency begins. Describe what is present. Stop.
The limit: 5-8 sentences. After that the room stops listening.

Quick Reference
If you're writing...
Ask yourself...
NPC dialogue
Does this person know what they're about to say? If yes, why?
A clue
Is this arriving sideways, or announcing itself?
GM prose
Am I saying what happens, or what it means?
A read-aloud
Does every sentence plant something or earn its place?
Ismara's notes
Is this the minimum number of words that does the job?
Anyone else
Are they thinking, or have they already thought?


The Manipulative Character Test
Calculating or performing: finished thoughts. Smooth sentences. Complete ideas. Warmth that arrives a beat too fast.
Genuine: broken sentences. They don't know where they're going. They say the wrong thing and don't notice.
The room feels the difference before anyone names it.
